		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=whadayawant&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>At 55 the best place to Solo is the Stalker camp in PoN.&nbsp;&nbsp;It's a hard camp to get but once you do it's well worth the wait.  Use harmony of nature on everything around because the agro range is tight....very tight.  Really the only mana effecient way to solo this camp is Charm.  I always start by pulling one of the two side mobs.  I pull with Glamour of Tunare and then run back a little ways, stop and cast snare, but you can take your chances with snaring them first but be warned that these mobs are extrememly resistant to magic until they are debuffed with Glamour.  Once snared, just run a little further back..stop..and cast Call of Karana.  After that tell your pet to sit while you run back and pull the mob on the opposite side.  Pull it the same way you did the pet.  Once it is snared tell  your pet to attack and then cast Engorging root on the mob.  Unless they've changed it since I was camping there, you have to do some damage to get exp from the pet, and casting a damage root on the mob will accomplish that for you.  Also at 55 charm is gonna break often and it's better to have one mob chasing you than it is to have them both.   The trick here is that you want your pet to end the fight with somewhere around half it's health, so if that means you have to heal it to win the fight be sure to do it.  Once the pet has killed the mob... tell the pet to sit.  Run as far away as you your spell range allows and cast invis on yourself.  This breaks the charm and your former pet will immediately come after you.  Snare should still be holding so you have plenty of time to cast engorging root on it and head back to the others.  With the old pet now rooted in place it's time to make a new pet and have it kill the old one.  Make the new pet the same way as the first..glamour, snare, charm, attack.  With the old pet at 1/2 health already the new pet shouldn't need any heals plus when  you rooted it you did your damage for the fight.  Have new pet kill old one...break charm....root pet and rinse and repeat for the next pet to kill it.   The idea is simple and repetitive but don't get me wrong..it's not easy...at least not at first and especially if you've never charmed before.  <br><br>Well thats how it's done.....now for the details....<br><br>The first two pulls are easy but the rest (with the exception of the one in the back, and farthest to the left) will always come with a friend or two unless you use harmony of nature on them first.  Until you know the camp I would highly recommend that you harmony every mob around the one you plan to pull because believe me...nothing is scarier than forgetting to do that and suddenly looking up to see the whole bunch of them flying towards you.   These guys hit for 500+ and usually quad so it's very important that you never let one get close to you....especially not your pet, because charm has a funny way of breaking when you least expect it and believe me you'll be dead before you realize what happened.  These guys run fast but not as fast as Sow or wolf form, which is what I would use since you don't slow down at the end of your heath in wolf form.   The spell list I always used was this:<br><br>1)Tunares Renewal<br>2)Ensnare<br>3)Engorging Roots<br>4)Glamour of Tunare<br>5)Call of Karana<br>6)Invisible<br>7)Harmony of Nature<br>8)Evac (until you get exodus)<br><br>I would not recommend using Savage Spirit until you become comfortable with the process of Charming these guys.  I'm not sure if there are 11 or 12 of them in the camp but you most likely will not be able to do more than 4 or 5 at level 55.  <br>Getting there is easy and safe if you always run high up on the wall all the way (just don't run past them or you'll run right into the middle of thier little love nest and that would not be good).  Thier camp is located on the other side of the waterfall from zone in...just keep going till you see them.  The most dangerous part of getting there is crossing the waterfall....if you're not up as high on the wall as possible you will agro whatever has spawned at the bottom of the falls.  The camp itself is a safe camp with a pretty long pull area that nothing ventures into unless pulled there.  I went from 55 to 60 in three days doing this camp but that was before they nerfed the solo exp.  Not sure what it is like now....but the camp is a great place to double up with a chanter or another druid.   Trust me when I say that it most definitely is not a good place to bring any type of melee classes (with the possible exception of maybe rangers who can do damage from a distance).  Maybe in a full group with a cleric that works but at 55, any melee who tries to fight one of these guys will get priority agro over your pet and will be dead before you can say &quot;/g Tunares Renewal on *insert dead guys name here*.  C3 is a must for doing this camp as well and having a partner to do it with means having someone to hold the camp when your c3 runs out.   <br><br>Anyway that is about it...I don't think I've forgotten anything important about the process.  Enjoy the camp...it's alot of fun once you get the hang of it.  Expect to die....alot at first...but don't worry the exp is so good you'll never miss it.  Also these guys drop diamonds, raw diamonds, and blue diamonds on a fairly regular basis so not only is the exp good....the $$$ is the best.   Do yourself a favor and don't sell any of the diamonds that drop until you ding 60 and then go sell them all and then spend the next hour or so shopping.  I had 2 stacks of diamonds, 1 stack of raw diamonds (give or take a few) and almost a stack of blue diamonds when i sold mine and I didn't start saving them till i was level 57.  Good Luck</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td><td align="right" id="fs8" >1 Replies</td></tr></table>
